## Request
Please introduce how public order and morals are handled in the United States, the United Kingdom, Germany, China, South Korea, and India, along with specific legal texts (preferably the original text and its English translation).
## Answaer by ChatGPT
Good—below How I compare how “public order and morals” (公序良俗 / public policy / good morals) are treated in six jurisdictions, and I give specific legal texts or leading authoritative sources (original language where available, plus an English rendering). I cite official sources or well-known translations so you can check the primary wording.
United States (common-law approach — public policy doctrine)
How it’s handled (summary).
The U.S. has no single statutory “public order and morals” clause equivalent to Japan’s Article 90. Rather, U.S. courts apply a public-policy doctrine (judge-made) to refuse enforcement of contracts or terms that offend public policy. The American Law Institute’s Restatement (Second) of Contracts summarizes the doctrine used by courts: a promise or term may be unenforceable if enforcement is outweighed by public policy interests. Courts balance private freedom of contract against public welfare. Open Casebook
Authoritative text (English): Restatement (Second) of Contracts §178 (summary text used by courts):
“A promise or other term of an agreement is unenforceable on grounds of public policy if legislation provides that it is unenforceable or the interest in its enforcement is clearly outweighed in the circumstances by a public policy against the enforcement of such terms.” Open Casebook
Representative case (historic): courts often cite principles such as ex dolo malo non oritur actio (no action arises from bad motive), and numerous U.S. state decisions apply this balancing test. For a teaching/summary source see the Restatement §178 text. Open Casebook
United Kingdom (common-law — public policy / illegality doctrine)
How it’s handled (summary).
In England & Wales the principle is judge-made: courts will not assist a claimant whose cause of action is founded on an illegal or immoral act (the maxim ex dolo malo non oritur actio). There is not a single civil code clause; instead the doctrine of illegality / public policy is developed by case law and shaped by statutes in specific areas (e.g., criminal, public order, obscenity). trans-lex.org+1
Foundational quote (Lord Mansfield, Holman v Johnson, 1775):
“The principle of public policy is this; ex dolo malo non oritur actio.” (Holman v Johnson (1775) 1 Cowp 341). trans-lex.org
Typical application: courts treat clauses or claims contrary to public policy (e.g., contracts to commit crimes, or agreements contrary to statutory public policy) as unenforceable; modern English cases refine when and how relief may nonetheless be available. Oxford Law Blogs
Germany (civil-law general clause: Bürgerliches Gesetzbuch (BGB))
How it’s handled (summary).
German civil law contains explicit general clauses that void legal transactions contrary to law or good morals. Two central provisions are § 134 BGB (statutory prohibition) and § 138 BGB (transactions contrary to good morals — sittenwidrig). These operate as bright-line rules: transactions violating statutes or fundamental moral standards are void. gesetze-im-internet.de+1
Original (German) + official English translation (from the Federal Ministry site):
§ 134 BGB (German):
“Ein Rechtsgeschäft, das gegen ein gesetzliches Verbot verstößt, ist nichtig, sofern sich nicht aus dem Gesetz ein anderes ergibt.”
English (official translation):
“A legal transaction that violates a statutory prohibition is void, unless the law leads to a different result.” gesetze-im-internet.de
§ 138 BGB (German):
“(1) Ein Rechtsgeschäft, das gegen die guten Sitten verstößt, ist nichtig.”
English (official translation):
“(1) A legal transaction that is contrary to good morals is void.” gesetze-im-internet.de+1
(Full official English BGB text available at the German government’s laws portal.) gesetze-im-internet.de
People’s Republic of China (Civil Code: general clause)
How it’s handled (summary).
China’s Civil Code (2020) explicitly requires civil actors to comply with the law and not to act against public order and good morals. The Civil Code contains a general principle that civil activities violating law, public order or good morals are prohibited — similar in role to Japan’s public-order clause. Enforcement and scope are informed by judicial interpretation and policy considerations. 全国人民代表大会+1
Original (Chinese) + English rendering (NPC / official PDF):
Civil Code, Article 8 (Chinese):
“民事主体从事民事活动，不得违反法律，不得违背公序良俗。”
English (translation):
“When conducting a civil activity, civil subjects shall not violate the law or offend public order or good morals.” 全国人民代表大会+1
(See the NPC/translated PDF of the PRC Civil Code for the official English rendering.) 全国人民代表大会+1
South Korea (Civil Act — general clause)
How it’s handled (summary).
Korean civil law contains an explicit general clause that voids juristic acts whose object is contrary to good morals and other social order. The civil-law provision functions similarly to the Japanese public-order clause: it is a general, open-textured norm that courts interpret against changing social standards and public policy. law.go.kr+1
Original (Korean) + English text (official site / government translation):
Civil Act, Article 103 (Korea) (Korean):
“선량한 풍속 기타 사회질서에 위반한 사항을 내용으로 하는 법률행위는 무효로 한다.”
English (official translation on government site):
“A juristic act which has for its object such matters as are contrary to good morals and other social order shall be null and void.” law.go.kr+1
(See the Korean government legal portal / KLRI for the official English rendering and judicial commentary.) e-Law+1
India (statutory test in contract law; constitutional public order)
How it’s handled (summary).
India uses statutory tests in contract law and constitutional limits to public freedoms. In contract law, Section 23 of the Indian Contract Act, 1872 declares that the consideration or object of an agreement is unlawful if it is immoral or opposed to public policy; such agreements are void. Separately, constitutional fundamental rights may be subject to reasonable restrictions in the interests of public order, decency and morality (see Article 19 restrictions). Thus India uses both codified statutory rules and constitutional public-order terms. indiacode.nic.in
Authoritative text (English — original statutory English text):
Indian Contract Act, 1872 — Section 23 (original English):
“The consideration or object of an agreement is lawful, unless — (among other things) — it is immoral, or opposed to public policy; …”
(Full statutory wording available from India Code / official sources.) indiacode.nic.in+1
Short comparative notes (practical teaching points for adult learners)
Civil-law jurisdictions (Germany, China, Korea) commonly embody public-order/morals as express general clauses in their civil codes (voiding transactions contrary to statute or morals). These are textual, broad provisions that courts apply and interpret. gesetze-im-internet.de+2全国人民代表大会+2
Common-law jurisdictions (U.S., UK) rely more on judge-made public-policy/illegality doctrines (with supporting statutes in specific fields). Courts balance private contractual freedom against the public interest and may refuse enforcement when policy dictates. The Restatement (Second) of Contracts §178 is a compact articulation used in the U.S.; Lord Mansfield’s formulation anchors the English approach. Open Casebook+1
India combines statutory contract rules (Section 23) with constitutional restrictions on fundamental rights in the name of public order, decency and morality. indiacode.nic.in
Sources & links (primary texts / authoritative translations)
United States: Restatement (Second) of Contracts §178 (authoritative summary used by U.S. courts). Open Casebook
United Kingdom: Holman v Johnson (1775) — classical authority on public policy / illegality. trans-lex.org
Germany: Bürgerliches Gesetzbuch (BGB) — §§134, 138 (official English translation available). gesetze-im-internet.de+1
China: Civil Code of the PRC (2020), Article 8 (Chinese text and English translation in NPC PDF). 全国人民代表大会+1
South Korea: Civil Act, Article 103 — “contrary to good morals and other social order” (official English rendering available from law.go.kr / KLRI). law.go.kr+1
India: Indian Contract Act, 1872, Section 23 (original English text on India Code). indiacode.nic.in+1
