Public Order and Morals — Comparative Extracts and Explanations
This document summarizes how "public order and morals" (公序良俗 / public policy / good morals) are treated in six jurisdictions: United States, United Kingdom, Germany, China, South Korea, and India.
It provides short explanations, selected primary text extracts (original language where applicable), and English renderings. Use this for teaching or reference in adult education.
United States — Common-law public policy (Restatement §178)
Summary:
U.S. courts apply a judge-made public-policy doctrine to refuse enforcement of contracts or claims that offend public policy. The Restatement (Second) of Contracts §178 summarizes the approach used by many courts.
Authoritative extract (English):
Restatement (Second) of Contracts §178 — Public policy
"A promise or other term of an agreement is unenforceable on grounds of public policy if legislation provides that it is unenforceable or the interest in its enforcement is clearly outweighed in the circumstances by a public policy against the enforcement of such terms."
Official reference:
American Law Institute (ALI) – Restatement (Second) of Contracts
Cornell Legal Information Institute summary
United Kingdom — Illegality / public policy doctrine (common law)
Summary:
English courts refuse assistance to claims founded on illegal or immoral acts; the doctrine is developed by case law rather than a single statute.
Classic authority (English):
Holman v Johnson (1775) 1 Cowp 341 (Lord Mansfield):
"The principle of public policy is this; ex dolo malo non oritur actio."
("No action arises from a bad cause.")
Official reference:
British and Irish Legal Information Institute (BAILII)
UK Government – Legislation Portal
Germany — Civil Code (Bürgerliches Gesetzbuch, BGB) §§134, 138
Summary:
German civil law contains explicit general clauses. Transactions violating statutory prohibitions (§134) or good morals (§138) are void.
Original (German) & English rendering:
§ 134 BGB (German):
"Ein Rechtsgeschäft, das gegen ein gesetzliches Verbot verstößt, ist nichtig, sofern sich nicht aus dem Gesetz ein anderes ergibt."
§ 134 BGB (English rendering):
"A legal transaction that violates a statutory prohibition is void, unless the law leads to a different result."
§ 138 BGB (German):
"Ein Rechtsgeschäft, das gegen die guten Sitten verstößt, ist nichtig."
§ 138 BGB (English rendering):
"A legal transaction that is contrary to good morals is void."
Official reference:
Gesetze im Internet – BGB (Federal Ministry of Justice, Germany)
People's Republic of China — Civil Code (2020), Article 8
Summary:
China's Civil Code contains a general principle requiring civil actors to observe law and public order/good morals.
Original (Chinese) & English rendering:

Civil Code, Article 8 (Chinese):
"民事主体从事民事活动，不得违反法律，不得违背公序良俗。"
Civil Code, Article 8 (English rendering):
"When conducting a civil activity, civil subjects shall not violate the law or offend public order or good morals.
Official reference:
NPC Official English Page – Civil Code of the People's Republic of China
South Korea — Civil Act, Article 103
Summary:
Korean Civil Act nullifies juristic acts whose object is contrary to good morals and other social order.
Original (Korean) & English rendering:

Civil Act, Article 103 (Korean):
"선량한 풍속 기타 사회질서에 위반한 사항을 내용으로 하는 법률행위는 무효로 한다."
Civil Act, Article 103 (English rendering):
"A juristic act which has for its object such matters as are contrary to good morals and other social order shall be null and void."
Official reference:
Korea Law Information Center (KLRI) – Civil Act (English Translation)
Law.go.kr (Korean Statutes Portal)
India — Indian Contract Act, 1872 — Section 23; Constitutional public order
Summary:
India combines statutory contract-law tests (Section 23) declaring agreements with immoral or public-policy-opposed objects void, and constitutional provisions limiting rights in the interests of public order, decency, and morality.
Authoritative extract (English — original):
Indian Contract Act, 1872 — Section 23:
"The consideration or object of an agreement is lawful, unless— (1) it is forbidden by law; or (2) it is of such a nature that, if permitted, it would defeat the provision of any law; or (3) it is fraudulent; or (4) it involves or implies injury to the person or property of another; or (5) the court regards it as immoral, or opposed to public policy."
Official reference:
IndiaCode – Indian Contract Act, 1872
Ministry of Law and Justice – Legislative Department
Comparative Teaching Notes for Working Adults
Civil-law countries (Germany, China, South Korea, Japan): Tend to have explicit statutory general clauses that void transactions violating statutory prohibitions or good morals — suitable for rule-based teaching and clear textual examples.
Common-law countries (U.S., UK): Rely on judge-made doctrines; teaching should emphasize case reasoning, balancing tests, and examples where courts refuse enforcement.
India: A hybrid—statutory contract law with constitutional public-order restraints.
